```javascript
(function () {
    'use strict';

    function initTinyMCE(selector) {
        if (typeof selector === 'undefined') {
            selector = 'textarea.tinymce';
        }

        if (typeof tinyMCE === 'undefined') {
            return;
        }

        var elements = document.querySelectorAll(selector);

        elements.forEach(function (element) {
            var config = JSON.parse(element.getAttribute('data-config'));
            if (config) {
                if (config.selector) {
                    console.warn('Overriding the selector in the TinyMCE config is not supported.');
                } else {
                    config.selector = '#' + element.id;
                }

                if (config.external_plugins) {
                    for (var key in config.external_plugins) {
                        if (config.external_plugins.hasOwnProperty(key)) {
                            var url = config.external_plugins[key];
                            tinyMCE.PluginManager.load(key, url);
                        }
                    }
                }

                // Initialize TinyMCE 6
                tinymce.init(config);
            }
        });
    }

    // Initialize TinyMCE on DOMContentLoaded
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function () {
        initTinyMCE();
    });

    // Initialize TinyMCE on elements added to the DOM after DOMContentLoaded
    var observer = new MutationObserver(function (mutations) {
        mutations.forEach(function (mutation) {
            if (mutation.addedNodes.length) {
                Array.prototype.forEach.call(mutation.addedNodes, function (node) {
                    if (node.nodeName === 'TEXTAREA') {
                        initTinyMCE();
                    }
                });
            }
        });
    });

    // Observe elements that may be added to the DOM after DOMContentLoaded
    observer.observe(document.body, {
        childList: true,
        subtree: true
    });
})();
```

In the completed code, we create a MutationObserver that observes changes to the document body. When a new textarea element is added, the observer calls the `initTinyMCE` function to initialize TinyMCE on the new element.

In `printf`, if you pass `NULL` as the first argument, it will print `(null)`.

Here's an example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int *ptr = NULL;
    printf("%p\n", ptr);  // prints: (null)
    return 0;
}
```

Note that `NULL` is a macro that represents the address of `0`, which is the address of the first byte of an `int` type. When you pass `NULL` to `printf`, it will print the memory address where `NULL` is stored, which is `(null)`.

However, if you try to print a `NULL` pointer as a string using `printf`, it will print `(null)` instead of the string "null". This is because `printf` expects a format specifier that matches the type of the argument, and in this case, the format specifier `%s` expects a string.

Here's an example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int *ptr = NULL;
    printf("%s\n", ptr);  // prints: (null)
    return 0;
}
```

In this case, `printf` will print `(null)` instead of the string "null" because `ptr` is a `NULL` pointer, and `printf` can't convert a `NULL` pointer to a string.

