Here's a simple implementation of the Naive Bayes classifier in Java without using any external libraries. This implementation includes loading the datasets from CSV files, training the model, and calculating the accuracy, precision, and recall.

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.util.*;

public class NaiveBayesClassifier {

    private static class Dataset {
        String[] features;
        String[] labels;

        public Dataset(String[] features, String[] labels) {
            this.features = features;
            this.labels = labels;
        }
    }

    private static class NaiveBayes {
        private Map<String, Map<String, Double>> priors;
        private Map<String, Map<String, Double>> likelihoods;

        public NaiveBayes(Dataset dataset) {
            priors = new HashMap<>();
            likelihoods = new HashMap<>();

            for (String label : Arrays.asList(dataset.labels)) {
                priors.put(label, new HashMap<>());
                likelihoods.put(label, new HashMap<>());

                for (int i = 0; i < dataset.features.length; i++) {
                    priors.get(label).put(dataset.features[i], 0.0);
                    likelihoods.get(label).put(dataset.features[i], 0.0);
                }
            }

            for (int i = 0; i < dataset.features.length; i++) {
                for (String label : Arrays.asList(dataset.labels)) {
                    double prior = priors.get(label).get(dataset.features[i]);
                    double likelihood = likelihoods.get(label).get(dataset.features[i]);

                    prior += 1;
                    likelihood += 1;

                    priors.get(label).put(dataset.features[i], prior / (dataset.labels.length + 1));
                    likelihoods.get(label).put(dataset.features[i], likelihood / (dataset.labels.length + 1));
                }
            }
        }

        public String classify(String[] feature) {
            double maxLikelihood = Double.NEGATIVE_INFINITY;
            String bestLabel = null;

            for (String label : priors.keySet()) {
                double likelihood = calculateLikelihood(label, feature);

                if (likelihood > maxLikelihood) {
                    maxLikelihood = likelihood;
                    bestLabel = label;
                }
            }

            return bestLabel;
        }

        private double calculateLikelihood(String label, String[] feature) {
            double likelihood = priors.get(label).get(feature[0]);

            for (int i = 1; i < feature.length; i++) {
                likelihood *= likelihoods.get(label).get(feature[i]);
            }

            return likelihood;
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dataset dataset1 = loadDataset("dataset1.csv");
        Dataset dataset2 = loadDataset("dataset2.csv");

        NaiveBayes classifier = new NaiveBayes(dataset1);

        double accuracy = calculateAccuracy(classifier, dataset2);
        double precision = calculatePrecision(classifier, dataset2);
        double recall = calculateRecall(classifier, dataset2);

        System.out.println("Accuracy: " + accuracy);
        System.out.println("Precision: " + precision);
        System.out.println("Recall: " + recall);
    }

    private static Dataset loadDataset(String filename) {
        List<String[]> features = new ArrayList<>();
        List<String[]> labels = new ArrayList<>();

        try (BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(filename))) {
            String line;
            while ((line = reader.readLine())!= null) {
                String[] values = line.split(",");

                if (values.length == 2) {
                    labels.add(values[0].trim());
                    features.add(values[1].trim().split("\\s+"));
                }
            }
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error loading dataset: " + e.getMessage());
        }

        Dataset dataset = new Dataset(features.toArray(new String[0]), labels.toArray(new String[0]));

        return dataset;
    }

    private static double calculateAccuracy(NaiveBayes classifier, Dataset dataset) {
        int correct = 0;

        for (String[] feature : dataset.features) {
            String label = classifier.classify(feature);

            if (label.equals(dataset.labels[Arrays.asList(dataset.labels).indexOf(feature)])) {
                correct++;
            }
        }

        return (double) correct / dataset.features.length;
    }

    private static double calculatePrecision(NaiveBayes classifier, Dataset dataset) {
        int truePositives = 0;
        int falsePositives = 0;

        for (String[] feature : dataset.features) {
            String label = classifier.classify(feature);

            if (label.equals(dataset.labels[Arrays.asList(dataset.labels).indexOf(feature)])) {
                truePositives++;
            } else {
                falsePositives++;
            }
        }

        return truePositives / (truePositives + falsePositives);
    }

    private static double calculateRecall(NaiveBayes classifier, Dataset dataset) {
        int truePositives = 0;
        int falseNegatives = 0;

        for (String[] feature : dataset.features) {
            String label = classifier.classify(feature);

            if (label.equals(dataset.labels[Arrays.asList(dataset.labels).indexOf(feature)])) {
                truePositives++;
            } else {
                falseNegatives++;
            }
        }

        return truePositives / (truePositives + falseNegatives);
    }
}
```

This code assumes that the CSV files have two columns: the feature values and the corresponding labels. The labels should be in the format "class1,class2,...,classN" where classN is the label for the corresponding feature values.

Note that this implementation uses a simple Naive Bayes classifier with a uniform prior distribution for each feature. In practice, you may want to use a more sophisticated prior distribution, such as a Gaussian distribution, or use a different classifier altogether.

Also, this implementation only calculates the accuracy, precision, and recall for the test dataset. In practice, you may want to use cross-validation to evaluate the performance of the classifier on unseen data.

