```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int testCases;
    cin >> testCases;

    while (testCases--) {
        int amount;
        cin >> amount;

        int denominations[] = {1000, 500, 200, 100, 50, 20, 10, 5, 2, 1};
        int count = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            count += amount / denominations[i];
            amount %= denominations[i];
        }

        cout << count << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This program works by iterating over the available denominations in descending order. For each denomination, it calculates how many bills of that denomination can be used by performing integer division (`amount / denominations[i]`) and updates the remaining amount (`amount %= denominations[i]`). The total count of bills is incremented by the number of bills used for each denomination.

The time complexity of this solution is O(n), where n is the number of denominations, and the space complexity is O(1) as it only uses a constant amount of space to store the denominations and the count.

